<TITLE> BNP leaders laud new standing committee </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 14 (bdnews24.com)  Top BNP leaders of the newly formed standing committee have termed the highest policy making body an 'integrated committee of youths and experienced'. They hoped the new committee will help steer the party forward by tackling big challenges under the leadership of chairperson Khaleda Zia. Khaleda Zia formed a 19-member national standing committee Sunday night bringing in 12 new faces. Ex-army chief Gen Mahbubur Rahman, a standing committee member, told bdnews24.com on Monday: "The new committee is an integration of experienced and young men. This is good. "We think the formation of the new committee is timely and appropriate," he said. A S M Hannan Shah said: "The leader has undoubtedly formed a good committee. I hope the party under the new committee will be more organised." He alleged those who had worked in favour of 1/11 changeover and against the chairperson also got places. He did not clarify. Former speaker Jamir Uddin Sircar said: "I was a standing committee member during the term of Ziaur Rahman (party's founder). I was not in the committee for sometime and now I am back again. For which I thank the leader." He hoped the committee will work to fulfill people's hope. Abdul Moyeen Khan expressed his gratitude to the leader. He said: "There is a combination of new and old ones in the committee that will make the party stronger." New senior joint secretary general Mirza Fakhrul Alamgir said: "In my opinion this is a good committee. The combination of new and old at the top level has taken place. Barkatullah Bulu, another new joint secretary general, said: "This is a good side that we have got some new faces. The leader has presented the party a good committee through her wisdom and prudence." The new faces are Tariqul Islam, ASM Hannan Shah, MK Anwar, Sarowari Rahman, Jamir Uddin Sircar, Mirza Abbas, Goyeshwar Chandra Roy, Abdul Moyeen Khan, Nazrul Islam Khan, Rafiqul Islam Miah and Salauddin Quader Chowdhury. The new committee will have a three-year term. bd
